a 1240","ABT 1242":"circa 1242","1301":"1301","1212":"1212","1244":"1244","1243":"1243","1219":"1219","Wavering,Kent,Eng":"Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","of Bishopsbourne, Kent, Eng":"Bishopsbourne, Kent, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"abt 1212–ABT 1273":"about 1212–about 1273","1212–1273":"1212–1273","1220–1271":"1220–1271","1240–1301":"1240–1301","1242–Male":"1242–Deceased","1244–1340":"1244–1340","1185–1243":"1185–1243","1194–1219":"1194–1219","BEF 1242/1243":"1243","ABT 1268":"about 1268","1242":"1242","1220":"1220","1340":"1340","1240":"1240","1185":"1185","1273":"1273","AFT 1219":"after 1219","1271":"1271","1194":"1194","abt 1212":"about 1212","ABT 1273":"about 1273","ABT 1240":"about 1240","ABT 1242":"about 1242","1301":"1301","1212":"1212","1244":"1244","1243":"1243","1219":"1219","Wavering,Kent,Eng":"Kent, England, United Kingdom","of Bishopsbourne, Kent, Eng":"Bishopsbourne, Kent, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hougham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Kent): habitational name from Hougham (Kent), or, less often, from Hougham (Lincolnshire). The Kent placename may derive from an Old English personal name <i>Huhha</i> or Old English <i>hōh</i> ‘heel, spur of land’ + <i>hām</i> ‘village, homestead’, while the Lincolnshire placename probably takes its name from Hough on the Hill (a nearby place called with Old English <i>haga</i> ‘hedge, enclosure’) + Old English <i>hām</i> ‘village, homestead’ or <i>hamm</i> ‘water meadow’."],"variants":[{"name":"Hufham","meanings":["Probably an altered form of English   Hougham  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert de Hougham was born about 1212, his father, Robert de Hougham, was 29 and his mother, de Boughton, was 20. He married Beatrice about 1268. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died about 1273, at the age of 63."},"et":{"abt 1212–ABT 1273":"umbes 1212–umbes 1273","1212–1273":"1212–1273","1220–1271":"1220–1271","1240–1301":"1240–1301","1242–Male":"1242–Surnud","1244–1340":"1244–1340","1185–1243":"1185–1243","1194–1219":"1194–1219","BEF 1242/1243":"1243","ABT 1268":"umbes 1268","1242":"1242","1220":"1220","1340":"1340","1240":"1240","1185":"1185","1273":"1273","AFT 1219":"pärast